{"contents":[{"parts":[{"text":"An 8-bit full adder is a digital circuit designed to compute the arithmetic sum of two eight-bit binary numbers along with an initial carry input. It is typically constructed by cascading eight individual one-bit full adders in a series where the carry out bit from each stage becomes the carry in bit for the next most significant position. For each bit position, the circuit processes three inputs to produce two outputs known as the sum bit and the carry out bit. This ripple carry architecture ensures that the final result represents a value between zero and five hundred ten when the final carry bit is included. The sum output provides the lower eight bits of the result, while the final carry out signifies an overflow or the ninth bit of the total sum. Module declaration will be like the following:module adder_8bit ( input logic [7:0] a, // First 8-bit operand input logic [7:0] b, // Second 8-bit operand input logic cin, // Carry-in output logic [7:0] sum, // 8-bit sum result output logic cout // Carry-out (overflow) );"}],"role":"user"}],"generationConfig":{"temperature":0.2},"systemInstruction":{"parts":[{"text":"You are an expert SystemVerilog verification engineer. Read the hardware specification and output a detailed JSON-formatted test plan. Include 'module_name', 'inputs', 'outputs', and an array of 'tests' (each with name, type, and description). Output ONLY valid JSON without markdown wrapping."}]}}
